{"title_page": "Jas Ram Singh", "text_new": "{{Infobox military person\n| honorific_prefix = [[Lieutenant Colonel]]\n| name          = Jas Ram Singh\n| honorific_suffix = [[Ashoka Chakra (military decoration)|AC]]\n| image         = \n| image_size    = \n| birth_date    = {{birth date and age |1935|03|01}}\n| birth_place   = Bhabokra Village, [[Bulandshahr]], [[Uttar Pradesh]], [[India]]\n| allegiance    = {{Flag|India}}\n| branch        = {{Army|India}}\n| serviceyears  = \n| rank          = [[File:Lieutenant Colonel of the Indian Army.svg|25px]] [[Lieutenant Colonel]]\n| servicenumber = \n| unit          = [[Rajput Regiment| 6 Rajput Regiment]]\n| awards        = [[File:Ashoka Chakra ribbon.svg|30px]] [[Ashoka Chakra (military decoration)| Ashoka Chakra]]\n}}\n\n[[Lieutenant colonel|Lieutenant Colonel]]  '''Jas Ram Singh''', [[Ashoka Chakra (military decoration)|AC]] (1st March 1935) was a retired [[Indian Army]] Officer and recipient of [[Ashoka Chakra (military decoration)|Ashoka Chakra]] the India's highest peace time military decoration.<ref>{{Cite web|url=PREVIEW\n4:40\nAshok Chakra Awardee Lt Col Jasram Singh's Inspiring Story {{!}} Bravery\nYouTube \u00b7 NationalDefence\nJan 30, 2018|title=|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> \n\n== Early Life ==\nLt Col Jas Ram Singh was born on 1st March 1935 at Bhabokra village in Bulandshahr District of Uttar Pradesh. His father, Shri Badan Singh was a simple farmer and instilled in his children honesty, integrity and simple living. In the absence of basic facilities and even a primary school in his village, Lt Col Jas Ram Singh had to struggle in his childhood. He had his primary education in another village after which he joined NREC in Khurja for his higher education.\n\n== Military Career ==\nHe joined the Army as a Signalman. After serving in a number of Signal Regiments, he was selected as an instructor in the [[Army Educational Corps]] where he continued till 1963. In the same year, he was commissioned as an Emergency Commissioned Officer from OTS, Madras into the [[Rajput Regiment]].\n\n== Operation in Mizo Hills ==\nIn 1968 Captain Jas Ram Singh was posted with [[Rajput Regiment]] in [[Mizoram]]. In the same year he was leading 16 Battalion\u2019s platoon of  Rajput Regiment in Mizo Hills. He received information that some militants were hidden in Mizo hills. After  receiving the information, he tried hard and came to know that near about 50 militants were present in a village in Mizo Hills. Captain Jasram Singh along with two platoons instantly headed towards the village. When they were about to reach the village, the platoons came under heavy militants fire from a dominating feature. Captain Jasram Singh individually led the assault and overran the militants \u2018position. After this courageous act militants abandoned position and fled away. They left behind two dead, six injured and a huge quantity of arms and ammunition. In this complete encounter, Captain Jasram Singh displayed most conspicuous bravery and leadership. For his bravery he received [[Ashoka Chakra (military decoration)|Ashoka Chakra Award]]. \n\n<br />\n\n== Reference ==\n<references />\n\n\n\n<br /><br />\n[[Category:1935 births]]\n[[Category:Indian Army personnel]]\n", "text_old": "[[Lieutenant colonel|Lieutenant Colonel]]  '''Jas Ram Singh''', [[Ashoka Chakra (military decoration)|AC]] (1st March 1935) was a retired [[Indian Army]] Officer and recipient of [[Ashoka Chakra (military decoration)|Ashoka Chakra]] the India's highest peace time military decoration.<ref>{{Cite web|url=PREVIEW\n4:40\nAshok Chakra Awardee Lt Col Jasram Singh's Inspiring Story {{!}} Bravery\nYouTube \u00b7 NationalDefence\nJan 30, 2018|title=|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> \n\n== Early Life ==\nLt Col Jas Ram Singh was born on 1st March 1935 at Bhabokra village in Bulandshahr District of Uttar Pradesh. His father, Shri Badan Singh was a simple farmer and instilled in his children honesty, integrity and simple living. In the absence of basic facilities and even a primary school in his village, Lt Col Jas Ram Singh had to struggle in his childhood. He had his primary education in another village after which he joined NREC in Khurja for his higher education.\n\n== Military Career ==\nHe joined the Army as a Signalman. After serving in a number of Signal Regiments, he was selected as an instructor in the [[Army Educational Corps]] where he continued till 1963. In the same year, he was commissioned as an Emergency Commissioned Officer from OTS, Madras into the [[Rajput Regiment]].\n\n== Operation in Mizo Hills ==\nIn 1968 Captain Jas Ram Singh was posted with [[Rajput Regiment]] in [[Mizoram]]. In the same year he was leading 16 Battalion\u2019s platoon of  Rajput Regiment in Mizo Hills. He received information that some militants were hidden in Mizo hills. After  receiving the information, he tried hard and came to know that near about 50 militants were present in a village in Mizo Hills. Captain Jasram Singh along with two platoons instantly headed towards the village. When they were about to reach the village, the platoons came under heavy militants fire from a dominating feature. Captain Jasram Singh individually led the assault and overran the militants \u2018position. After this courageous act militants abandoned position and fled away. They left behind two dead, six injured and a huge quantity of arms and ammunition. In this complete encounter, Captain Jasram Singh displayed most conspicuous bravery and leadership. For his bravery he received [[Ashoka Chakra (military decoration)|Ashoka Chakra Award]]. \n\n<br />\n\n== Reference ==\n<references />\n\n\n\n<br /><br />\n", "name_user": "Koushik Pain", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jas_Ram_Singh"}
{"title_page": "Lisa Mainiero", "text_new": "{{Use American English|date=May 2018}}{{Use mdy dates|date=May 2018}}\n{{Infobox academic\n| name               = Lisa Mainiero\n|birth_name=Lisa Adeline Mainiero\n|birth_date={{Birth date and age|1957|01|18}}\n| alma_mater         = [[Yale University]] {{small|(Ph.D., 1983)}}\n| thesis_title       = Coping With Powerlessness: Power Balancing Strategies Employed by Men and Women Under Conditions of Related Dependency in Organizational Settings\n| thesis_url         = https://search.proquest.com/docview/303195683\n| thesis_year        = 1983 \n|doctoral_advisor=[[J. Richard Hackman]]| discipline         = {{Plainlist|\n*Management\n*Women's studies}}\n| workplaces         =[[Fairfield University Dolan School of Business]]\n}}\n\n'''Lisa Adeline Mainiero''' (born January 18, 1957)<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.isni.org/isni/0000000083018206|title=ISNI 0000000083018206 Mainiero, Lisa A. (born 1957-01-18)|website=www.isni.org|access-date=2018-06-17}}</ref> is an American writer and academic in the field of management. Her research focuses on women in management. Mainiero is considered one of the first researchers to investigate romance in the workplace.\n\n== Education ==\nMainiero completed a doctorate in organizational behavior from [[Yale University]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/19946253/asbury_park_press/|title=Study says office romance can help|last=|first=|date=1987-09-01|work=Asbury Park Press|access-date=2018-05-09|language=en|via=Newspapers.com}}</ref> She worked with [[Victor Vroom]] on a pre-dissertation project. In 1983, Maniero completed her dissertation titled ''Coping With Powerlessness: Power Balancing Strategies Employed by Men and Women Under Conditions of Related Dependency in Organizational Settings''. [[J. Richard Hackman]] was the chair of her dissertation committee along with members, [[Rosabeth Moss Kanter]], and Martha Glenn Cox.<ref>{{Cite document|title=Coping With Powerlessness: Power Balancing Strategies Employed by Men and Women Under Conditions of Related Dependency in Organizational Settings|last=Mainiero|first=Lisa|date=1983|language=en|id = {{ProQuest|303195683}}}}</ref>\n\n== Career ==\nMainiero is a Full Professor of Management at [[Fairfield University Dolan School of Business]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/19940797/the_los_angeles_times/|title=Despite the Risks, Office Romances Remain Attractive|last=Taylor|first=Frances Grandy|date=1989-08-07|work=The Los Angeles Times|access-date=2018-05-09|via=Newspapers.com}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.fairfield.edu/lassochannel/academic/profile/index.lasso?id=135|title=Dr. Lisa A. Mainiero|website=Fairfield University|access-date=2018-05-09}}</ref> Her research focuses on women in management.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/19946504/tampa_bay_times/|title=Smitten workers may have hearts in right place|last=Taylor|first=Frances Grandy|date=1989-07-24|work=Tampa Bay Times|access-date=2018-05-09|language=en|via=Newspapers.com}}</ref> Mainiero is one of the first researchers to investigate romance in the workplace.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/19946703/the_palm_beach_post/|title=Beauty can hinder a competent woman|last=Schellhardt|first=Timothy D.|date=1991-11-03|work=The Palm Beach Post|access-date=2018-05-09|language=|via=Newspapers.com}}</ref> She has appeared on [[Good Morning America]], [[The Oprah Winfrey Show]], and [[Larry King Live]]. Formerly, Mainiero served on the editorial board and was the research translation editor for the [[Academy of Management Perspectives|''Academy of Management Executive'']]. She was a division and program chair of the Women in Management Division of the Academy of Management.<ref name=\"Mainiero 2006\">{{Cite book|title=The Opt Out Revolt: Whe People are Leaving Companies to Create Kaleidoscope Careers|last=Mainiero|first=Lisa A.|last2=Sullivan|first2=Sherry E.|date=2006|publisher=Davies-Black Pub|isbn=9780891063322|location=Mountain View, Calif.|pages=|oclc=243598672}}</ref>\n\n== Selected works ==\n\n=== Books ===\n\n* {{Cite book|title=Office Romance: Love, Power & Sex in the Workplace|last=Mainiero|first=Lisa|date=1989|publisher=Macmillan|isbn=1501109677|location=|pages=|oclc=894026258}}<ref>Reviews of ''Office Romance: Love, Power & Sex in the Workplace'':\n* {{Cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/19940655/tallahassee_democrat/|title=Corporate Love: Office romances work their way into company time|last=Fichtner|first=Margaria|date=1989-07-11|work=Tallahassee Democrat|access-date=|via=Newspapers.com}}\n* {{Cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/19940575/the_anniston_star/|title=Companies ease 'relations' rules|last=Rubin|first=Sylvia|date=1991-04-11|work=The Anniston Star|access-date=|via=Newspapers.com}}\n* {{Cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/19940523/the_salina_journal/|title=Romance on the job embraced by more firms|last=The New York Times|first=|date=1991-03-24|work=The Salina Journal|access-date=|via=Newspapers.com}}\n* {{Cite journal|last=Zlatos|first=Christy|date=May 1989|title=Office Romance: Love, Power & Sex in the Workplace|url=|journal=Library Journal|volume=114|issue=9|pages=81|via=}}\n* {{Cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/19946033/the_jackson_sun/|title=Clocking in to work and love not corporate approved|last=|first=|date=1989-08-07|work=The Jackson Sun|access-date=|via=Newspapers.com}}\n</ref>\n* {{Cite book|title=Developing Managerial Skills in Organizational Behavior|last=Mainiero|first=Lisa A.|last2=Tromley|first2=Cheryl L.|date=1994|publisher=Prentice Hall|isbn=013226028X|edition=2|location=Englewood Cliffs|pages=|oclc=402350565}}\n* {{Cite book|title=Managing Power Through Lateral Networking|last=Brindle|first=Margaret|last2=Mainiero|first2=Lisa A.|date=2000|publisher=Quorum|isbn=0585385807|location=Westport, Conn.|pages=|oclc=49569484}}<ref>Reviews of ''Managing Power Throu