ance in the workplace.\n\n== Education ==\nMainiero completed a doctorate in organizational behavior from [[Yale University]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/19946253/asbury_park_press/|title=Study says office romance can help|last=|first=|date=1987-09-01|work=Asbury Park Press|access-date=2018-05-09|language=en|via=Newspapers.com}}</ref> She worked with [[Victor Vroom]] on a pre-dissertation project. In 1983, Maniero completed her dissertation titled ''Coping With Powerlessness: Power Balancing Strategies Employed by Men and Women Under Conditions of Related Dependency in Organizational Settings''. [[J. Richard Hackman]] was the chair of her dissertation committee along with members, [[Rosabeth Moss Kanter]], and Martha Glenn Cox.<ref>{{Cite document|title=Coping With Powerlessness: Power Balancing Strategies Employed by Men and Women Under Conditions of Related Dependency in Organizational Settings|last=Mainiero|first=Lisa|date=1983|language=en|id = {{ProQuest|303195683}}}}</ref>\n\n== Career ==\nMainiero is a Full Professor of Management at [[Fairfield University Dolan School of Business]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/19940797/the_los_angeles_times/|title=Despite the Risks, Office Romances Remain Attractive|last=Taylor|first=Frances Grandy|date=1989-08-07|work=The Los Angeles Times|access-date=2018-05-09|via=Newspapers.com}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.fairfield.edu/lassochannel/academic/profile/index.lasso?id=135|title=Dr. Lisa A. Mainiero|website=Fairfield University|access-date=2018-05-09}}</ref> Her research focuses on women in management.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/19946504/tampa_bay_times/|title=Smitten workers may have hearts in right place|last=Taylor|first=Frances Grandy|date=1989-07-24|work=Tampa Bay Times|access-date=2018-05-09|language=en|via=Newspapers.com}}</ref> Mainiero is one of the first researchers to investigate romance in the workplace.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://